Example of a t-test

library(inductive)
library(tidyverse)
data(big_five)
Age Gender Extraversion Neuroticism Agreeableness Conscientiousness Openness
36 m 3.0 1.9 3.4 3.3 3.6
30 f 3.1 3.4 3.1 2.7 3.8
23 m 3.4 2.4 3.6 3.0 3.2
54 m 3.3 4.2 3.6 3.0 2.9
24 f 3.0 2.8 3.0 3.3 3.5
14 f 2.8 3.5 3.2 3.3 3.6 
big_five %>% 
  sta_t(Extraversion ~ Neuroticism)
#> $result
#>     t.value       df  p.value   conf.low  conf.high    cohen.d
#> 1 -1.054057 295.4322 0.292718 -0.1634245 0.04942449 -0.1054057
#> 
#> $obj
#> 
#>  Welch Two Sample t-test
#> 
#> data:  x and y
#> t = -1.0541, df = 295.43, p-value = 0.2927
#> alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
#> 95 percent confidence interval:
#>  -0.16342449  0.04942449
#> sample estimates:
#> mean of x mean of y 
#>     3.076     3.133 
#> 
#> 
#> attr(,"class")
#> [1] "list"  "stats"
big_five %>% 
  sta_t(Extraversion ~ Gender)
big_five %>% 
  sta_t(x = Extraversion, y = Neuroticism) 
sta_t(x = big_five$Extraversion, y = big_five$Neuroticism)

The obj argument

res <- big_five %>% 
  sta_t(Extraversion ~ Neuroticism)
res %>% 
  pluck("result")
#>     t.value       df  p.value   conf.low  conf.high    cohen.d
#> 1 -1.054057 295.4322 0.292718 -0.1634245 0.04942449 -0.1054057
res %>% 
  pluck("obj")
#> 
#>  Welch Two Sample t-test
#> 
#> data:  x and y
#> t = -1.0541, df = 295.43, p-value = 0.2927
#> alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
#> 95 percent confidence interval:
#>  -0.16342449  0.04942449
#> sample estimates:
#> mean of x mean of y 
#>     3.076     3.133
big_five %>% 
  sta_t(Extraversion ~ Neuroticism, obj = FALSE)
#>     t.value       df  p.value   conf.low  conf.high    cohen.d
#> 1 -1.054057 295.4322 0.292718 -0.1634245 0.04942449 -0.1054057
